  "published": "2019-08-29",
  "runtimeMin": 62,
  "format": "Sean Fennessey and Amanda Dobbins walk through Netflix's suddenly stacked fall slate and the theatrical-window fight around it, argue about whether The Irishman's three-and-a-half-hour runtime means anything, then each build a five-deep list of the movie they're most anticipating out of Venice, Telluride, TIFF, and the New York Film Festival.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "Netflix's stacked fall slate, and the theatrical-window fight",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "The Laundromat",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "Soderbergh's Panama Papers docudrama, written by Scott Z. Burns, with Meryl Streep in a bucket hat and Gary Oldman. Gets a three-week theatrical window before landing on Netflix."
        },
        {
          "title": "Dolemite Is My Name",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "Eddie Murphy plays Rudy Ray Moore in Craig Brewer's biopic, written by Scott Alexander and Larry Karaszewski. Murphy's first SNL hosting gig in over 30 years is timed right alongside it."
        },
        {
          "title": "The King",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "David Michôd's Henriad adaptation, written with Joel Edgerton, with Timothée Chalamet as Henry V and Robert Pattinson as the Dauphin. Premieres at TIFF."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Irishman",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "Scorsese's three-and-a-half-hour mob epic with De Niro, Pesci, and Pacino, premiering at the New York Film Festival. The hosts spend a good chunk of the show debating whether runtime has anything to do with quality."
        },
        {
          "title": "Atlantics",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "Mati Diop's Cannes prizewinner, mentioned only in passing here."
        },
        {
          "title": "Earthquake Bird",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "Wash Westmoreland directs an adaptation neither host had heard much about yet; he co-directed Still Alice."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Two Popes",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "Fernando Meirelles directs Jonathan Pryce and Anthony Hopkins as Pope Francis and Pope Benedict, from an Anthony McCarten script."
        },
        {
          "title": "Marriage Story",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "Noah Baumbach's semi-autobiographical divorce drama. Both hosts single it out as the one they're most excited for and agree not to spoil it for each other."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "Is there a blockbuster anywhere near this year's Oscars?",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Once Upon a Time in Hollywood",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "Comes up twice: once as a runtime comparison for The Irishman, once as one of the only films in the conversation with real box-office weight."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Farewell",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "A24's slow-build hit, already out for weeks. The hosts think its rollout has been close to perfect even without a splashy fall-festival premiere."
        },
        {
          "title": "Ford v Ferrari",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "James Mangold's racing drama with Matt Damon and Christian Bale. Sean calls it the one title here that could plausibly do real business."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "topfive",
